@node History

@{u}@{b}V2.04b@{uu}@{ub}

-
A VERY STUPID bug removed. LZH files wouldn't be extracted and repacker would create an empty LZX file. (Reported by Russ Harbert)



@{u}@{b}V2.04@{uu}@{ub}

+
@{b}LHA2LZX@{ub} can handle @{b}DMS, ZIP, ARJ, ARC, ZOO, GZ@{ub} and @{b}Z@{ub} files too - no need for @{b}ZIP2LZX@{ub} anymore... If you only wants to repack @{b}LHA@{ub} files, use the option "@{b}ONLYLHA@{ub}". To enable @{b}DMS@{ub} packing, you will have to use the option "@{b}DMS@{ub}".

+
If an error occurs, @{b}LHA2LZX@{ub} will tell you a bit more about it.

+
Now it's possible to delete the old file before saving the @{b}LZX@{ub} file. This will make the repacker useful on @{b}VERY@{ub} filled disks... Ofcourse the original @{b}LhA@{ub} file will be kept if something went wrong. (Suggested by Mikael Ludwigsson)

+
You can keep the old file no matter what by using the option "@{b}KeepOld@{ub}". (Also suggested by Mikael)

-
Fixed a small error in the text (i hope nobody noticed that :)

-
Sorry about distributing V2.03 inside a trashcan drawer, the program isn't @{b}*THAT*@{ub} bad! :-)



@{u}@{b}Changes from the original REPACK script@{uu}@{ub}

+
@{b}LHA2LZX@{ub} will also handle those terrible slow @{b}ZIP{ub} files.

+
The scripts will check the return code to see if the archiver was successful. 

@{b}WARNING:@{ub}
Because @{b}ZIP{ub} is a PC program compiled for Amiga, my version of @{b}zip{ub} doesn't support result codes. Therefore, it won't tell @{b}ZIP2LZX@{ub} if something went wrong. Anyway, if you can get hold of an @{b}unzip@{ub} which handles this, the repacking of @{b}ZIP@{ub} files will be *TOTALLY* safe.

By the way, if some error occurs, it's probably because your HD is full... So just keep some mb free to avoid the problem...

+
Now it's safe to set TEMPDIR to anything you like (as HD1:) since the script will create a dir called _LZX_TEMP.

+
Now it's possible to use "" to repack the current dir.

+
Totally safe if you uses T: for the temporary files...

+
Some minor fixes which i don't seems to remember...

@endnode

